{"guideId":"4e10d849-187f-49b6-8f22-23fa8ce5d220","chunks":[{"content":"FAST NUCES Islamabad Campus AI2002 – Artificial Intelligence Genetic Algorithm for Solving a Maximization Problem AI2002 – Artificial Intelligence FAST NUCES Islamabad Campus Spring 2026 Abstract This document demonstrates the application of a Genetic Algorithm (GA) to solve a lin- ear maximization problem. A complete step-by-step numerical trace is presented, covering initialization, evaluation using fitness-proportionate selection, roulette-wheel selection, one- point crossover, and gene mutation. The example shows how the average population fitness increases across generations, guiding the search toward the global optimum. Problem Formulation Suppose we wish to maximize the following objective function: f (a, b, c, d) = 3a + 2b + 5c + 4d where a, b, c, d are integers restricted to the range [0, 10]. The theoretical maximum is f = 140, achieved when a = b = c = d = 10. Since this is a maximization problem, the fitness of a chromosome is taken directly as its objective function value – chromosomes with higher f values are more fit and have a higher probability of selection. Each chromosome encodes a candidate solution as four genes: a b c d GA Parameters: Population size = 4, Crossover rate ρc = 0.50, Mutation rate ρm = 0.10 Step 1. Initialization We randomly generate 4 chromosomes, each with gene values drawn uniformly from [0, 10]: Chromosome[1] = [a; b; c; d] = [2; 8; 3; 5] Chromosome[2] = [a; b; c; d] = [7; 1; 6; 2] Chromosome[3] = [a; b; c; d] = [4; 5; 1; 9] Chromosome[4] = [a; b; c; d] = [9; 3; 7; 4] Page 1 -- 1 of 5 -- FAST NUCES Islamabad Campus AI2002 – Artificial Intelligence Step 2. Evaluation We compute the objective function value for each chromosome: F obj[1] = 3(2) + 2(8) + 5(3) + 4(5) = 6 + 16 + 15 + 20 = 57 F obj[2] = 3(7) + 2(1) + 5(6) + 4(2) = 21 + 2 + 30 + 8 = 61 F obj[3] = 3(4) + 2(5) + 5(1) + 4(9) = 12 + 10 + 5 + 36 = 63 F obj[4] = 3(9) + 2(3) + 5(7) + 4(4) = 27 + 6 + 35 + 16 = 84 For maximization, Fitness[i] = F obj[i] directly: Total Fitness = 57 + 61 + 63 + 84 = 265 Step 3. Selection The selection probability for each chromosome is: P [i] = Fitness[i] / Total P [1] = 57/265 = 0.2151 P [2] = 61/265 = 0.2302 P [3] = 63/265 = 0.2377 P [4] = 84/265 = 0.3170 Chromosome 4 holds the largest share of the roulette wheel, reflecting its highest fitness. Cumulative probabilities for the roulette-wheel process are: C[1] = 0.2151 C[2] = 0.2151 + 0.2302 = 0.4453 C[3] = 0.4453 + 0.2377 = 0.6830 C[4] = 0.6830 + 0.3170 = 1.0000 We generate four random numbers R ∈ [0, 1] and map each to a chromosome: Spin R Interval Selected 1 0.147 R < C[1] Chromosome 1 2","embedding":[-0.07987654954195023,0.022220872342586517,-0.05052579939365387,-0.07661470770835876,-0.019180653616786003,-0.043316036462783813,0.0014913531485944986,-0.010479331016540527,-0.08813781291246414,0.042475972324609756,0.023777758702635765,-0.06562165915966034,0.06988894939422607,-0.03377090021967888,-0.027579667046666145,0.051661744713783264,-0.04158007353544235,0.02842799946665764,-0.15559551119804382,-0.11183900386095047,-0.054995421320199966,0.020422320812940598,0.08672508597373962,-0.022309821099042892,-0.08222050964832306,-0.0367148220539093,0.029092391952872276,0.02812931314110756,-0.046343568712472916,-0.0827057808637619,0.06790822744369507,0.08754775673151016,0.09931311756372452,-0.02639765664935112,-0.05552716180682182,-0.014638133347034454,-0.15393958985805511,0.008503398858010769,0.058669980615377426,-0.000900197250302881,-0.020543977618217468,0.03707212209701538,0.03600575029850006,0.039617057889699936,0.046968866139650345,0.046249426901340485,-0.08702225983142853,-0.014650372788310051,0.03659359738230705,-0.005344958044588566,-0.05822126939892769,0.003188339527696371,-0.06206755340099335,0.013018949888646603,0.03018820658326149,-0.06892410665750504,0.006878708954900503,-0.09534642100334167,0.028073661029338837,-0.030754949897527695,0.051930513232946396,0.0196284931153059,0.